Inference concerning the mean

Normal population-varaince known

Suppose a sample of size n from normal population with mean \(\mu\) and known variance \(\sigma^2\)

\(H_{0}: \mu = \mu_{0}\) \(H_{1}: \mu \ne \mu_{0}\)

if population not normal we can use this test if n is large >30

Shapiro-Wilk normality test

average longevity of bulb is 4 years, standard deviation 0.16, random sample of 40 gave mean 3.45 Two tailed test example mn islam 11.5 alpha = 0.05

# normal test
x_bar <- 3.45
n <- 40
mu_not <- 4
sigma <- 0.16
z_statistics  <- (x_bar - mu_not)/(sigma/sqrt(n))
z_statistics
## [1] -21.74066
# 0.05
# 0.025
# 1- 0.025
qnorm(c(0.025, 0.975))
## [1] -1.959964  1.959964
# critical value -1.96
2*pnorm(-abs(z_statistics))
## [1] 8.467452e-105

Reject null hypothesis

mu_not - 1.96*(sigma/sqrt(n))
## [1] 3.950415
mu_not + 1.96*(sigma/sqrt(n))
## [1] 4.049585
  1. compairing test statistics
  2. confidence interval
  3. p value calculate

normal population variance unknown-sample size small

\(t = \dfrac{\overline{x} - \mu_{0}}{s/\sqrt(n)}\) with n-1 df t distribution instead of normal

example mn inslam book 11.11

tensile strength of steel averge 120 pounds, sample 25, sample mean 110 pounds, sample variance 144

x_bar <- 110
n <- 25
mu_not <- 120
s <- 12
t_statistics  <- (x_bar - mu_not)/(s/sqrt(n))
t_statistics
## [1] -4.166667
# from t distribution
# p value
2*pt(-abs(t_statistics),df=n-1)
## [1] 0.0003455224
# critical region
qt(c(.025, .975), df=n-1)
## [1] -2.063899  2.063899

reject null hypothesis

difference between two mean

testing equality of two population means

assumptions populations are normal with known but unequal variance drawn independentlly from the populations

example 11.14

trival women 12, non trival 15, average children respectively 4.5, 3.4,population variance 1 and 1.5 respectively

n1 <- 12
n2 <- 15
x1_bar <- 4.5
x2_bar <- 3.4
sigma_sq_1 <- 1
sigma_sq_2 <- 1.5

z <- (x1_bar-x2_bar)/(sqrt((sigma_sq_1/n1)+sigma_sq_2/n2))
z
## [1] 2.569047
# critical region
qnorm(c(0.025,0.975))
## [1] -1.959964  1.959964
2*pnorm(-abs(z))
## [1] 0.01019788

example 11.18

batsman average 70.2, sample standard deviation 8.4, in 16 matches in dhaka, 62.7 std 7.7 in another 14 match in chittagong

difference 7.5 due to regional difernce or real difference

n1 <- 16
n2 <- 14
x1_bar <- 70.2
x2_bar <- 62.7
sigma_sq_1 <- 8.4^2
sigma_sq_2 <- 7.5^2

sp_sq <- ((n1-1)*sigma_sq_1 + (n2-1)*sigma_sq_2)/(n1+n2-2)
sp_sq
## [1] 63.91607
t <- (x1_bar -x2_bar)/(sqrt(sp_sq)*sqrt(1/n1+1/n2))
t
## [1] 2.563419
# critical region
qt(c(0.025,0.975), n1+n2-2)
## [1] -2.048407  2.048407
pt(-abs(t),df=n1+n2-2)
## [1] 0.008012206

example 11.20

sales99 <- c(126, 56, 86, 62, 96, 36, 52, 50, 35, 53)
sales20 <- c(123, 49, 79, 59, 92, 35, 48, 48, 32, 50)

d1 <- sales99 - sales20
d1
##  [1] 3 7 7 3 4 1 4 2 3 3
d1_sq <- d1^2
d_bar <- sum(d1)/length(sales99)
n <- length(sales99)
d_bar
## [1] 3.7
s_d <- sqrt((sum(d1^2) - n * d_bar^2)/(n-1))
s_d
## [1] 1.946507
t <- d_bar / (s_d / sqrt(n))
t
## [1] 6.010987
qt(c(0.025,0.975), n-1)
## [1] -2.262157  2.262157

Test concerning proportions

\(H_{0}: p = p_{0}\) \(H_{1}: p => p_{0}\)

example 11.28

protien deficiency at most 0.75, true for 244 out of 300. sig 0.01

p_caret <- round(244/300,2)
p_not <- 0.75
q_not <- 1 - p_not
n <- 300
z <- (p_caret - p_not)/sqrt(p_not*q_not/n)
z
## [1] 2.4
abs(qnorm(0.01))
## [1] 2.326348
heads <- rbinom(1, size = 100, prob = .5)
prop.test(heads, 100)          # continuity correction TRUE by default
## 
##  1-sample proportions test with continuity correction
## 
## data:  heads out of 100, null probability 0.5
## X-squared = 0.25, df = 1, p-value = 0.6171
## alternative hypothesis: true p is not equal to 0.5
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.4280225 0.6296465
## sample estimates:
##    p 
## 0.53
prop.test(heads, 100, correct = FALSE)
## 
##  1-sample proportions test without continuity correction
## 
## data:  heads out of 100, null probability 0.5
## X-squared = 0.36, df = 1, p-value = 0.5485
## alternative hypothesis: true p is not equal to 0.5
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.4328886 0.6248918
## sample estimates:
##    p 
## 0.53
## Data from Fleiss (1981), p. 139.
## H0: The null hypothesis is that the four populations from which
##     the patients were drawn have the same true proportion of smokers.
## A:  The alternative is that this proportion is different in at
##     least one of the populations.

smokers  <- c( 83, 90, 129, 70 )
patients <- c( 86, 93, 136, 82 )
prop.test(smokers, patients)
## 
##  4-sample test for equality of proportions without continuity
##  correction
## 
## data:  smokers out of patients

## sample estimates:
##    prop 1    prop 2    prop 3    prop 4 
## 0.9651163 0.9677419 0.9485294 0.8536585

fishers exact test

## Agresti (1990, p. 61f; 2002, p. 91) Fisher's Tea Drinker
## A British woman claimed to be able to distinguish whether milk or
##  tea was added to the cup first.  To test, she was given 8 cups of
##  tea, in four of which milk was added first.  The null hypothesis
##  is that there is no association between the true order of pouring
##  and the woman's guess, the alternative that there is a positive
##  association (that the odds ratio is greater than 1).


TeaTasting <-
matrix(c(3, 1, 1, 3),
       nrow = 2,
       dimnames = list(Guess = c("Milk", "Tea"),
                       Truth = c("Milk", "Tea")))
chisq.test(TeaTasting)
## Warning in chisq.test(TeaTasting): Chi-squared approximation may be incorrect
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test with Yates' continuity correction
## 
## data:  TeaTasting
## X-squared = 0.5, df = 1, p-value = 0.4795
chisq.test(TeaTasting,simulate.p.value = TRUE)
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test with simulated p-value (based on 2000
##  replicates)
## 
## data:  TeaTasting
## X-squared = 2, df = NA, p-value = 0.4648
fisher.test(TeaTasting, alternative = "greater")
## 
##  Fisher's Exact Test for Count Data
## 
## data:  TeaTasting
## p-value = 0.2429
## alternative hypothesis: true odds ratio is greater than 1
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.3135693       Inf
## sample estimates:
## odds ratio 
##   6.408309
## => p = 0.2429, association could not be established
